parsed_response.summary:
Goldman Sachs and JPMorgan both came away constructive on Alphabet post Q3’25, framing the quarter as evidence that AI is currently an accelerant (not a disruptor) to the core ad engine while Cloud is emerging as a second durable profit pool. GS reiterates Buy and raises its 12-month PT to $330 (from $288) , while JPM reiterates Overweight and raises its Dec-26 PT to $340 (from $300) .

On fundamentals, both highlight Search resilience and improving investor confidence around the AI search transition. Q3 Google Search & Other grew +14.5% YoY , and GS notes management disclosed both paid clicks and CPCs grew +7% YoY . JPM similarly emphasizes that query growth and paid clicks (+7%) accelerated, arguing that AI Overviews/AI Mode are improving the experience and driving higher frequency and more complex queries, with monetization “about the same rate” as traditional search (in JPM’s view) . The key debate both implicitly address is whether AI reduces clicks per query; JPM’s stance is that any click pressure is offset by higher query growth and better lead quality, supporting pricing .

Cloud is the other major pillar. GS calls Cloud the highlight, citing +34% YoY revenue growth and ~23% segment operating margins  (Q3 Cloud revenue growth shown as +33.5% YoY in the quarter detail) . JPM also flags the $155bn backlog and notes it may not yet reflect all recently announced deal expansions, implying continued upside to forward Cloud revenue . For valuation, this matters because sustained Cloud growth with expanding margins increases consolidated operating leverage and supports premium multiples.

The principal near-term offset is capital intensity. GS highlights management raised FY25 capex guidance to $91–93bn (from ~$85bn) and reiterated elevated capital intensity into 2026 . GS also points to the P&L consequence: Q3 depreciation expense increased $1.6bn YoY (+41%) with guidance for slight acceleration in Q4 . In other words, even if operating margins are managed, higher capex and D&A can pressure near-term FCF conversion and create sensitivity around the timing of AI monetization.

The two firms’ valuation frameworks differ but converge on a similar conclusion: Alphabet deserves a premium multiple given scale, growth, and margin profile. GS’s $330 PT is based on an equal blend of 22.0x EV/GAAP EBITDA and 30.0x EV/FCF-SBC (discounted) , while JPM’s $340 PT is based on ~27.5x 2027E GAAP EPS of $12.43 . For senior bankers, the combined takeaway is that valuation is most levered to (1) the durability of Search monetization through the AI format transition, (2) Cloud backlog-to-revenue conversion with margin expansion, and (3) the capex/D&A path that determines how quickly AI-driven growth translates into incremental FCF.
